Rating: 4
This is the best use of Next Day Turkey I've tried! I subbed celeriac for the celery since I used what I had for the Thanksgiving meal and I added 3 medium red potatoes. I used just shy of 3 cups of the giblet stock I had made two days previously in my slow cooker and it was the perfect amount. The filling wasn't too liquid or too stiff. The biscuit topping, as many others have noted, is the real star of the dish. I used King Arthur White Whole Wheat flour (moved to this flour as my all-purpose years ago and never looked back) and they emerged flavorful and crisp, yet still on the lighter side. I think I used slightly more cheese since I eyeballed it rather than measured as I was grating - maybe an extra 1/4 cheddar and an extra 1/8 parm - but it worked wonderfully. I ended up with 9 spooned biscuits on top. Our family of 3 only ate 1/3rd of the dish so, for storage, I separated biscuits and filling and will marry them again in reheating. I'm glad I did so because they would have turned to mush sitting on top of the pie in the fridge. I'm glad to say that the biscuits are still crisp on top the next day. Overall, this recipe is a keeper! It's going into rotation this winter as it's satisfying, tasty, and a great use of left over roasts!

